03:08.160 --> 03:12.160
that this guy right next to her, Sean Carter, is Jay-Z.

03:12.160 --> 03:13.520
If that's the case,

03:13.520 --> 03:18.160
then sentence number two can be informative to her.

03:18.160 --> 03:21.360
It has, as Frege says, cognitive value.

03:21.360 --> 03:24.240
You can really learn something from sentence number two.

03:24.240 --> 03:26.720
This woman, Ellen, can really learn something

03:27.520 --> 03:31.040
by discovering or being told that Sean Carter is Jay-Z.

03:32.160 --> 03:35.120
So I'm writing here that sentence two is informative.

03:35.120 --> 03:38.320
It can teach her something in the way that sentence one never could.

03:38.320 --> 03:39.840
Sean Carter is Sean Carter.

03:39.840 --> 03:41.200
Yes, of course.

03:41.200 --> 03:43.840
As long as these two names, here and here,

03:43.840 --> 03:46.720
are being used in the same sense to mean the same thing,

03:46.720 --> 03:49.440
well then one is totally banal and uninformative,

03:49.440 --> 03:52.000
whereas two can be informative.

03:53.120 --> 03:55.840
